\begin_layout Subsection
Qur'anic Concepts Ontology 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Qur'anic Ontology is also a project of Leeds university done by 
\noun on
Kais Dukes.

\noun default
 It uses knowledge representation to define the key concepts in the Qur'an,
 and shows the relationships between these concepts using predicate logic.
 The fundamental concepts in the ontology are based on the knowledge contained
 in traditional sources of Qur'anic analysis, including the hadīth of the
 prophet Muhammad , and the Tafssir (Qur'anic exegesis) of 
\emph on
ibn kathīr
\emph default
.
 Named entities in verses, such as the names of historic people and places
 mentioned in the Qur'an, are linked to concepts in the ontology as part
 of named entity tagging.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As well as listing the major concepts in the Qur'an, the ontology also defines
 a set of semantic relations between these concepts.
 The most important relation is the set membership relation "instance" in
 which one concept is defined to be an instance or individual member of
 another group.
 For example the relation 
\emph on
"Satan is a jinn"
\emph default
 in the ontology would represent the knowledge contained in the Qur'an that
 the individual known as
\emph on
 Satan
\emph default
 belongs to the set of sentient creations named the 
\emph on
jinn
\emph default
.
 Other concepts in the ontology and grouped into logical categories, according
 to the properties that they share.
 For example, the Sun, Earth and Moon are classified under "Astronomical
 Body":
